sourceQuestion:
Consider the following snapshot of a system running n concurrent processes. Process i is holding X_i instances of a resource R, 1 <= i <= n. Assume that all instances of R are currently in use. Further, for all i, process i can place a request for at most Y_i additional instances of R while holding the X_i instances it already has.

Of the following conditions, which one guarantees that no deadlock will occur?

A. For all i: X_n < Y_n (i.e., every process holds fewer than it can additionally request)
B. X_i + X_k < Max{Y_j | 1 <= j <= n} for all i, k
C. Min{X_i | 1 <= i <= n} >= Max{Y_k | 1 <= k <= n}
D. Min{X_i + Y_i | 1 <= i <= n} >= Max{X_k | 1 <= k <= n}

Two shared resources R_1 and R_2 are used by processes P_1 and P_2. Each process has a certain priority for accessing each resource. Let T_{ij} denote the priority of process P_i for accessing resource R_j. A process P_i can snatch a resource from process P_k if T_{ij} > T_{kj} (for the resource R_j in question).

Given the following priority assignments:
I.   T_{11} > T_{21}, T_{12} > T_{22}
II.  T_{11} > T_{21}, T_{12} < T_{22}
III. T_{11} < T_{21}, T_{12} > T_{22}
IV.  T_{11} < T_{21}, T_{12} < T_{22}

Which of the following conditions ensures that deadlock will NOT occur?

A. (I) and (II) only
B. (III) and (IV) only
C. (I) and (IV) only
D. (II) and (III) only

